        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "A '''causal network''' is a Bayesian network with an explicit requirement that the relationships be causal. The additional semantics of the causal networks specify that if a node ''X'' is actively caused to be in a given state ''x'' (an action written as do(''X''&nbsp;=&nbsp;''x'')), then the probability density function changes to the one of the network obtained by cutting the links from the parents of ''X'' to ''X'', and setting ''X'' to the caused value ''x''.<ref name=pearl2000/> Using these semantics, one can predict the impact of external interventions from data obtained prior to intervention."
